Introduction to Principle Components Analysis

In supervised learning a set of features \(\{X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_3\}\) are used to predict an outcome variable \(Y\). In contrast, unsupervised learning refers to situations where we only have a set of features \(\{X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_3\}\) and do not have an associated response variable. In these situations, focusing on prediction makes little sense and we shift our goals towards to trying to discover interesting trends or patterns amongst the available features.

Principle Components Analysis (PCA) is a widely used unsupervised learning method (with applications to supervised learning too!). The method has uses in many disciplines, see the very detailed PCA Wikipedia page for a description of these applications.

In this lab we will use the factoextra package to perform principle component analysis and visualize the results.

1. What are Principle Components?

Consider data consisting of \(n\) measurements of \(p\) variables. When \(p\) is large it becomes difficult to visualize the relationships between variables. If \(p = 10\), there already 45 different two variable combinations, presenting a time-consuming barrier to using bivariate methods like scatterplots or the correlation coefficient to find patterns in the data. Rather than exhaustively looking at many subsets/combinations of the available variables, PCA finds a low-dimensional representation of the data that contains as much of the original variation as possible.

The main idea of PCA is as follows: Each of the \(n\) observations live in \(p\)-dimensional space (for example if \(p = 3\) we could plot the location of each data point on a 3-dimensional scatterplot), but not all of these \(p\) dimensions are equally interesting. Here, interesting refers to how much the observed data varies in that dimension. The goal of PCA is to establish a new, smaller set of derived dimensions that are interesting as possible. Ideally, most of the variability in the data exists 2 or 3 of these dimensions, allowing for visual representations that capture most of what is going on in a data set.

The new derived dimensions, or principle components, are linear combinations of the original variables. The first principle component looks like:

\[Z_1 = \phi_11 X_1 + \phi_21 X_2 + \ldots + \phi_p1 X_p\]

The coefficients \(\phi_11, \ldots, \phi_p1\) are called the loadings of the first principle component. We wont go into details on how the loadings of a principle component are calculated, but they can be found rather easily using eigenvalue decompositions, a standard technique in linear algebra.

A conceptual example of how PCA works is shown below:

In scenario A, the variables X and Y are redundant. If you know an observations X-value, you pretty much know its Y-value. Wed expect that only one-dimension (ie: a line) could effectively describe the variability in both X and Y due to their obvious dependence. Contrast this with scenario B, where there is low redundancy in the two variables and one-dimension would not do a good job capturing the variation in the data.

This figure shows the first principle component (red) and second principle component (blue) for each scenario. These components are the newly derived dimensions. For scenario A, we can justifiably omit the second dimension because it contains very little new information. Retaining just the first principle component is akin to projecting the data onto the red line. However, in scenario B, relying on only the first component is undesirable, wed lose roughly half of the variability in the original data!

2. US Arrest Data Example

The loadings of the top principle components can be used to identify patterns in the data, especially when these components describe most of the variation in the data. As an example, well analyze data from the 50 US States by looking for relationships between assault, murder, and rape arrest rates per 100,000 residents. Well also include the proportion of the states population living in urban areas. We that expect some, or all, of these variables are correlated, making PCA a sensible choice.

data(USArrests)
head(USArrests)
##            Murder Assault UrbanPop Rape
## Alabama      13.2     236       58 21.2
## Alaska       10.0     263       48 44.5
## Arizona       8.1     294       80 31.0
## Arkansas      8.8     190       50 19.5
## California    9.0     276       91 40.6
## Colorado      7.9     204       78 38.7

In R, PCA can be performed using the prcomp function. In this example, the loadings of each principle component are stored in the object P. The argument scale = TRUE is used to rescale each variable to have a variance of 1, which is needed to put variables with different units on the same scale. For the majority of applications, rescaling is a necessary step for PCA to produce sensible results.

P <- prcomp(USArrests, scale = TRUE)
P
## Standard deviations (1, .., p=4):
## [1] 1.5748783 0.9948694 0.5971291 0.4164494
## 
## Rotation (n x k) = (4 x 4):
##                 PC1        PC2        PC3         PC4
## Murder   -0.5358995  0.4181809 -0.3412327  0.64922780
## Assault  -0.5831836  0.1879856 -0.2681484 -0.74340748
## UrbanPop -0.2781909 -0.8728062 -0.3780158  0.13387773
## Rape     -0.5434321 -0.1673186  0.8177779  0.08902432

Studying the components (PC1 PC4), we discern that the first principle component roughly describes the overall rate of crimes, as the loadings are large and roughly equal for the three crime variables, and smaller for the variable UrbanPop. The second principle component roughly describes the urbanization of a state, as the variable UrbanPop receives most of the weight in this component.

A quick way to visualize the first two principle components is the biplot function. The argument scale = 0 adjusts the scale of the component directions (the upper and right axes) to match their loadings; while cex = .75 adjusts the size of each plotted points text.

biplot(P, scale = 0, cex = .75)

More elegant visuals can be created using the factoextra package:

fviz_pca_biplot(P, repel = TRUE, # Avoid text overlapping
                col.var = "red", # Variables color
                col.ind = "black")  # Individuals color

The state names indicate each observations normalized score on the first two principle components. States in the upper left have low scores in the first principle component (meaning they have high overall rates of crime) and high scores in the second principle component (meaning they have low urbanization).

The red arrows depict the loadings of each variable. For example, the loading for UrbanPop is -0.28 in the first principle component and -0.83 in the second component, the red label of UrbanPop is centered at (-0.28, -.83) on the scale depicted on the top and right axes of the graph, which describes the loadings.

We can use the biplot to describe the key characteristics of each data point. For example, Florida is high crime and about average in urbanization; while West Virginia is low crime and not very urban.

Use the biplot to describe the crime and urbanization of California and Iowa.

3. How Many Components?

In the US states example, we used PCA to project 4-dimensional data into two dimensions. But it is important to consider how much information is lost by using only the first two principle components. Or, phrased differently, how much variability in the data is not contained in the first two principle components?

The fviz_eig function will produce a scree plot:

fviz_eig(P, addlabels = TRUE)

From the scree plot, we can see that first two principle components contain just under 90% of the variability in these data. This suggests plotting the data in two-dimensions (those derived from our first two principle components) is an effective summary of all of all the variables.

Deciding how many components to use depends upon the application. It is common practice to look at the scree plot for a leveling-off point. In the US Arrests example, most of the variation is in the first two principle components with sizeable dropoff between components two and three, so it is reasonable to use just the first two components.

Note: The percentages on the scree plot come directly from the eigenvalues, we can find them ourselves using the standard deviations given by prcomp:

P$sdev^2/sum(P$sdev^2)
## [1] 0.62006039 0.24744129 0.08914080 0.04335752

4. An Example From Psychology

PCA allows for effective visualizations when the data can be reduced to three or fewer principle components. However, this is not the only use of PCA. In this example, we will explore data collected from an interactive online personality test. The data involve the big-five personality traits, which are openness to experiences, conscientiousness, extraversion, agreeableness, and neuroticism.

The personality questionnaire used to collect these data asks participants to rate 50 statements on a five-point scale (1 = disagree, 3 = neutral, 5 = agree). There are 10 statements specifically designed to measure each of the big five traits. The questions, along with more detailed information on the data, can be found here: codebook link)

big5 <- read.delim("https://remiller1450.github.io/data/big5data.csv")

P2 <- prcomp(big5[, 8:ncol(big5)]) # Exclude the first 7 columns, which are demographics

fviz_eig(P2, addlabels = TRUE)

From the scree plot, five components stand out (with the first really standing out) before a noticeable drop in explained variability. Our next step is to look at which personality questions are contributing to each of these five components. We could do this by inspecting the loadings, but sorting through loadings for all 50 questions is time consuming. Instead well use the function fviz_contrib to find the top contributing questions for each principle component of interest.

fviz_contrib(P2, choice = "var", axes = 1, top = 6) # Top 6 contributors to the first component

We see that five of the top six contributors (and all of the first four) are questions from the E series. This is not a coincidence, psychologists have named this personality dimension Extroversion, and these questions were specifically designed to measure this trait!

The remainder of the big-five are shown below:

library(gridExtra) ## Used to arrange multiple ggplots

n <- fviz_contrib(P2, choice = "var", axes = 2, top = 6)  # Second component (Neuroticism)

c <- fviz_contrib(P2, choice = "var", axes = 3, top = 6) # Third component (Conscientiousness)

e <- fviz_contrib(P2, choice = "var", axes = 4, top = 6) # Forth component (Openness to Experiences)

a <- fviz_contrib(P2, choice = "var", axes = 5, top = 6) # Fifth component (Agreeableness)

grid.arrange(n,c,e,a, nrow = 2) ## Function for arranging ggplots into one grid

6. Practice - Characterizing Places to Live

The places related data were assembled by Boyer and Savageau (1981), who scored various cities across the US with the goal of objectively classifying different cities.

places <- read.csv("https://remiller1450.github.io/data/places.csv")
head(places)

The nine rating criteria used are: Climate and Terrain, Housing, Health Care and Environment, Crime, Transportation, Education, The Arts, Recreation, Economics.

For all but two of the above criteria, the higher the score, the better; for Housing and Crime, the lower the score the better.

The scores are computed based upon the following items:

  • Climate and Terrain: very hot and very cold months, seasonal temperature variation, heating- and cooling-degree days, freezing days, zero-degree days, ninety-degree days.
  • Housing: utility bills, property taxes, mortgage payments.
  • Health Care and Environment: per capita physicians, teaching hospitals, medical schools, cardiac rehabilitation centers, comprehensive cancer treatment centers, hospices, insurance/hospitalization costs index, fluoridation of drinking water, air pollution.
  • Crime: violent crime rate, property crime rate.
  • Transportation: daily commute, public transportation, Interstate highways, air service, passenger rail service.
  • Education: pupil/teacher ratio in the public K-12 system, effort index in K-12, academic options in higher education.
  • The Arts: museums, fine arts and public radio stations, public television stations, universities offering a degree or degrees in the arts, symphony orchestras, theatres, opera companies, dance companies, public libraries.
  • Recreation: good restaurants, public golf courses, certified lanes for tenpin bowling, movie theatres, zoos, aquariums, family theme parks, sanctioned automobile race tracks, pari-mutuel betting attractions, major- and minor- league professional sports teams, NCAA Division I football and basketball teams, miles of ocean or Great Lakes coastline, inland water, national forests, national parks, or national wildlife refuges, Consolidated Metropolitan Statistical Area access.
  • Economics: average household income adjusted for taxes and living costs, income growth, job growth.

Our analysis goal is to find trends and characterize individual cities using fewer variables.
